{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"16c26c11-3166-4e90-908c-fcd805788ce4","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. You create a custom `Window` subclass and override the corresponding methods:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI `Window` override |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` / `OnDeactivated()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `OnActivated()` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n        // replaces OnStart\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnDeactivated()\n    {\n        base.OnDeactivated();\n        // replaces OnSleep\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n        // replaces OnResume\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class, override `CreateWindow`:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n        => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n}\n```\n\n**Key distinction:** `Deactivated`/`Activated` fire when the app loses/gains focus, while `Stopped`/`Resumed` fire when it's fully backgrounded/foregrounded. Pick whichever matches your original intent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ecd16203-70f7-4a87-af19-4a43841b9f99","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. The `Application` class no longer has those virtual methods in the same way. Instead, you work with `Window` events or platform-specific lifecycle hooks.\n\n\nThe `Window` class is where the lifecycle is now managed. You can override `CreateWindow()` in your `Application` and hook into window lifecycle events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying`. You can also subclass `Window` and override the corresponding lifecycle methods directly, or use the `ILifecycleBuilder` approach for more granular control.","outputTokens":825,"requestId":"0458:21FCE6:A987A3:C285B1:6A027A38"},"id":"6d5a623a-ddfe-45e3-9848-dde85b02d6ba","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:54:32.943Z","parentId":"cdc0f788-806c-43f9-b1fd-ee4a7cad72df"}
